response:
 Let's label the exits following the arrows (all except in regions $J$ and $K$) as $1$, $2$, $3$ from left to right (horizontal axis) and start with labeling all regions. Let $b$ be the total probability of a chip getting sent along (or not along) $b$. 
[asy]
label("$A$", (2,-1));
label("$3$", (4,0));
label("$B$", (6,2));
label("$2$", (8,0));
label("$C$",  (10,-4));
label("$4$", (7,4));
label("$1$",  (5,-8));
label("$2$",  (2,-7));
label("$J$",  (0,11));
label("$3$", (2,11));
label("$J$", (2,-15));
label("$4$", (0,20));
label("$A$", (17,-1));
label("$3$", (19,0));
label("$B$", (21,2));
label("$2$", (23,0));
label("$C$", (25,-4));
label("$4$", (22,4));
[/asy]
We see the following probability distribution:
\begin{align*}
b&=\frac12\left(\frac12+b\right) & \tag{a-->b}\\
c&=\frac12\left(\frac12+b\right)+\frac12\left(\frac12+c\right) & \tag{b-->c}\\
a&=\frac12\left(\frac12+b\right)+\frac12\left(\frac12+c\right)+\frac12\left(\frac12+a\right) & \tag{c-->a}\\
j&=\frac12\left(\frac12+b\right)+\frac12\left(\frac12+c\right)+\frac12\left(\frac12+j\right)+\frac12\left(\frac12+j\right) & \tag{d-->j->B}\\
k&=\frac12\left(\frac12+b\right)+\frac12\left(\frac12+c\right)+\frac12\left(\frac12+j\right)+\frac12\left(\frac12+k\right) & \tag{d-->r-->K}\\
j&=\frac12\left(\frac12+b\right)+\frac12\left(\frac12+c\right)+\frac12\left(\frac12+2j\right) & \tag{d-->j->C}
\end{align*}
Simplifying, we get
\begin{align*}
b&=\frac23 \\
c&=\frac89 \\
a&=\frac{34}{27} \\
j&=\frac{56}{27} \\
k&=\frac{64}{27} \\
\frac{k}{a+k}&=\frac{8}{17}
\end{align*}
so the probability is $\boxed{\frac{8}{17}}$.

Here are the probabilities of landing in each pond:
- Pond $B$: $\frac{5}{17}$
- Pond $C$: $\frac{12}{17}$
- Pond $J$: $\frac{6}{17}$
- Pond $K$: $\frac{5}{17}$

These probabilities can also be computed by starting at the left. Computing P(correct-->$,+B,+A)$ yields $\frac{c+1}{2}=\frac{1+c+c^2+c^4}{2^{5}}$ which gives $c=\dfrac{-1+\sqrt{5}}{2}$ and $b=\dfrac{2}{2+c}= \dfrac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}\approx1.618$.  Since $j=c^3$ and $k=c^4$ and $j+k=1$, then $j=\dfrac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}=\dfrac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}$.  The desired probability is $\boxed{\frac{\sqrt{5}+1}{2}=1.61803398...}$.

